# Accessibility

## ARIA Labels
- All interactive elements must have ARIA labels
- Use semantic HTML elements when possible
- Provide labels for form inputs
- Describe button actions clearly

## Keyboard Navigation
- All interactive elements must be keyboard accessible
- Provide visible focus indicators
- Support Tab navigation
- Implement keyboard shortcuts (Cmd/Ctrl + Enter, etc.)

## Focus Management
- Manage focus when modals/dialogs open/close
- Return focus to trigger element after closing
- Don't trap focus unnecessarily
- Provide skip links for navigation

## Screen Reader Support
- Use semantic HTML (nav, main, article, etc.)
- Provide alt text for images
- Describe dynamic content changes
- Use ARIA live regions for announcements

## Patterns

### Accessible Button
```typescript
<Button
  aria-label="Create new room"
  onClick={handleCreate}
>
  Create Room
</Button>
```

### Accessible Form
```typescript
<label htmlFor="room-name">Room Name</label>
<input
  id="room-name"
  aria-required="true"
  aria-describedby="room-name-error"
/>
{error && <div id="room-name-error" role="alert">{error}</div>}
```

### Keyboard Shortcuts
```typescript
useEffect(() => {
  const handleKeyDown = (e: KeyboardEvent) => {
    if ((e.metaKey || e.ctrlKey) && e.key === 'Enter') {
      handleSubmit()
    }
  }
  window.addEventListener('keydown', handleKeyDown)
  return () => window.removeEventListener('keydown', handleKeyDown)
}, [])
```

## Color Contrast
- Ensure sufficient color contrast (WCAG AA minimum)
- Don't rely on color alone to convey information
- Test with color blindness simulators

## Testing
- Test with keyboard only (no mouse)
- Test with screen reader (VoiceOver, NVDA)
- Use automated accessibility tools (axe, Lighthouse)
- Manual testing is essential
